net.happybrackets.core.control

Class TextControl

  • java.lang.Object
    • net.happybrackets.core.control.DynamicControlParent
      • net.happybrackets.core.control.TextControl
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    TextControlSender

    public class TextControl
extends DynamicControlParent
    This class encapsulates the functionality of DynamicControl classes of type ControlType.TEXT in a simple API
    All Text controls with the same name and ControlScope will respond to a message send. For example: For example, consider two TextControls with the same ControlScope and name
    When the control receives the value, it will be passed through to the valueChanged(String) listener that is implemented when the class is created.
    For example 
     TextControl control1 = new TextControl(this, "Read", "");
 TextControl control2 = new TextControl(this, "Read", "") {
     @Override
    public void valueChanged(String control_val) {
        System.out.println("Read " + control_val);
    }
};

 control1.setValue("This is text");

    Will cause the valueChanged(String) function to be called with the new value, causing Read This is text to be printed to standard output.
    The control can also schedule messages to be sent at a time in the future by adding the time to the message using an absolute time in the setValue(String, double) function. Eg
    control1.setValue ("Hi There", HB.getSchedulerTime() + 1000); // this will set control1 value, as well as all other TextControls with same ControlScope and name, to "Hi There" 1 second in the future
    Setting the value within the HappyBrackets control display is effected by typing a new value in and pressing ENTER or RETURN If you do not require a handler on the class, override the valueChanged(String) function

        public void setValue(java.lang.String val)
        Set the value for the control. This will pass the message on to all other DynamicControl with matching name, type and ControlScope and call valueChanged(String). 
         TextControl control1 = new TextControl(this, "Read", "");
 TextControl control2 = new TextControl(this, "Read", "") {
     @Override
    public void valueChanged(String control_val) {
        System.out.println("Read " + control_val);
    }
 };

 control1.setValue("This is text");

        Will cause the valueChanged(String) function to be called with the new value, causing Read This is text to be printed to standard output.
        Parameters:
        val - the value to set to

      • setValue

        public void setValue(java.lang.String val,
                     double scheduler_time)
        set the value for the control at a specific time. Identical to the setValue(String) with the exception that the valueChanged(String) event will be caused at the HBScheduler scheduled time passed in.
        For example, the following code will cause matching DynamicControl objects to respond 1 second in the future control1.setValue ("Hi There", HB.getSchedulerTime() + 1000); // this will set control1 value, as well as all other TextControls with same ControlScope and name, to "Hi There" 1 second in the future
        Parameters:
        val - the value to set to
        scheduler_time - the scheduler time this is supposed to occur at
